28
0:01:32.237,000 --> 0:01:34,000
This is her 21st day at sea.

29
0:01:34.536,000 --> 0:01:36,000
At this point, she'd covered over 1,000 miles,

30
0:01:37.299,000 --> 0:01:39,000
had had no radio contact in more than two weeks

31
0:01:39.969,000 --> 0:01:42,000
following a storm that disabled all her long-range communications systems

32
0:01:43.409,000 --> 0:01:44,000
just five days in.

33
0:01:45.123,000 --> 0:01:47,000
Most days looked like this.

34
0:01:47.144,000 --> 0:01:5,000
At this point, she'd rowed over 200,000 strokes,

35
0:01:50.905,000 --> 0:01:52,000
fighting the current and the wind.

36
0:01:53.227,000 --> 0:01:56,000
Some days, she traveled as little as 15 feet.

37
0:01:56.71,000 --> 0:01:57,000
Yeah.

38
0:01:58.219,000 --> 0:02:,000
And as frustrating as those days were,

39
0:02:00.866,000 --> 0:02:03,000
other days were like this.

40
